To install Docker on an EC2 instance and explore Docker commands, you can follow these steps:

Connect to your EC2 instance: Use SSH to connect to your EC2 instance.

Update the package index: Run the following command to update the package index:
    >sudo apt update -y

Install Docker: Install Docker using the following commands:
    >sudo apt install -y docker

Start the Docker service: Start the Docker service using the following command:
    >sudo service docker start

Enable Docker service: Enable the Docker service to start on boot:
    >sudo systemctl enable docker

Verify Docker installation: Check if Docker is installed correctly by running:
    >docker --version

Now that Docker is installed on your EC2 instance, you can explore various Docker commands to manage images, containers, volumes, and networks.

Here are some commonly used Docker commands:

docker images: List all the images available on the system.
    >docker images

docker ps: List all the running containers.
    >docker ps

docker ps -a: List all containers (running and stopped).
    >docker ps -a

docker run: Create and start a new container from an image.
    >docker run <image_name>

docker stop: Stop a running container.
    >docker stop <container_id>

docker rm: Remove one or more containers.
    >docker rm <container_id>

docker volume ls: List all volumes.
    >docker volume ls

docker network ls: List all networks.
    >docker network ls

docker exec: Run a command inside a running container.
    >docker exec -it <container_id> <command>
